        "# Introduction\n",
        "\n",
        "Regression analysis is one of the most widely used statistical techniques. In Python, **`statsmodels`** provides R-style formula interfaces, detailed summary tables, and a rich set of diagnostic tools — making it the go-to library for inferential regression.\n",
        "\n",
        "This document covers:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Simple and multiple OLS regression\n",
        "- Interpreting coefficients and the summary table\n",
        "- Model diagnostics (residuals, normality, homoscedasticity, multicollinearity)\n",
        "- Polynomial and interaction terms\n",
        "- Logistic regression\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# What is Regression Analysis?\n",
        "\n",
        "## Core Concept\n",
        "\n",
        "Regression analysis is a statistical method used to **model and quantify the relationship between a dependent variable (outcome) and one or more independent variables (predictors)**. At its heart, regression answers the question: *\"How does Y change when X changes, holding everything else constant?\"*\n",
        "\n",
        "The most fundamental form is **Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)** linear regression, which fits a straight line (or hyperplane in multiple dimensions) through observed data by minimising the sum of squared residuals — the vertical distances between each data point and the fitted line:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\hat{\\boldsymbol{\\beta}} = \\arg\\min_{\\boldsymbol{\\beta}} \\sum_{i=1}^{n} \\left(y_i - \\mathbf{x}_i^\\top \\boldsymbol{\\beta}\\right)^2\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "## Types of Regression\n",
        "\n",
        "| Type | Use Case | Example |\n",
        "|------|----------|---------|\n",
        "| **Simple Linear** | One predictor, continuous outcome | `mpg ~ wt` |\n",
        "| **Multiple Linear** | Several predictors, continuous outcome | `mpg ~ wt + hp + cyl` |\n",
        "| **Polynomial** | Non-linear curvature in one predictor | `mpg ~ wt + I(wt²)` |\n",
        "| **Interaction** | Effect of X₁ depends on X₂ | `mpg ~ wt * am` |\n",
        "| **Logistic** | Binary outcome (0/1) | `am ~ mpg + wt` |\n",
        "| **Poisson / GLM** | Count or proportion data | claims, rates |\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Four OLS Assumptions (LINE)\n",
        "\n",
        "For OLS estimates to be unbiased and efficient (BLUE — Best Linear Unbiased Estimator), four assumptions must hold:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **L**inearity — the relationship between predictors and outcome is linear in parameters.\n",
        "2. **I**ndependence — observations are independent of each other (no autocorrelation).\n",
        "3. **N**ormality — the residuals $\\varepsilon_i$ are approximately normally distributed.\n",
        "4. **E**qual variance (Homoscedasticity) — the spread of residuals is constant across all fitted values.\n",
        "\n",
        "Violating these assumptions doesn't necessarily invalidate the model, but it does affect the reliability of standard errors, p-values, and confidence intervals. The diagnostics section of this document tests each assumption explicitly.\n",
        "\n",
        "## What Regression Can and Cannot Do\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-important}\n",
        "## Correlation ≠ Causation\n",
        "Regression quantifies **association**, not causation. A statistically significant coefficient means the predictor is linearly related to the outcome in the sample — it does not prove that X *causes* Y. Causal claims require additional design considerations (randomisation, instrumental variables, etc.).\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Regression **can**:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Estimate the average change in Y per unit change in X, controlling for other variables\n",
        "- Quantify uncertainty in estimates via standard errors and confidence intervals\n",
        "- Test hypotheses about individual coefficients (t-test) or the model as a whole (F-test)\n",
        "- Predict new outcomes given predictor values\n",
        "\n",
        "Regression **cannot**:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Establish causality from observational data alone\n",
        "- handle predictors that are perfectly correlated (multicollinearity causes the design matrix to be singular)\n",
        "- Extrapolate reliably far beyond the range of the training data\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# Python vs R for Regression\n",
        "\n",
        "Both Python and R are excellent choices for regression analysis. The right tool depends on your workflow, team, and goals.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Advantages of Python\n",
        "\n",
        "**1. General-purpose ecosystem**\n",
        "Python is a full-stack programming language. The same environment used for regression can handle data ingestion, API calls, web scraping, building dashboards (Dash, Streamlit), deploying machine learning models, and automating pipelines — with no context switching.\n",
        "\n",
        "**2. Machine learning integration**\n",
        "Python's `scikit-learn`, `XGBoost`, `LightGBM`, and `PyTorch` ecosystems are the industry standard for predictive modelling. When a project evolves from inference (statsmodels) toward prediction and deployment, everything stays in one language.\n",
        "\n",
        "**3. Industry adoption and job market**\n",
        "Python consistently ranks as the most popular language in data science hiring. Teams in tech, finance, and consulting typically standardise on Python, making code sharing and collaboration easier.\n",
        "\n",
        "**4. Performance and scalability**\n",
        "Libraries like `NumPy`, `Polars`, and GPU-backed frameworks make Python well-suited for large datasets that would strain R's in-memory model.\n",
        "\n",
        "**5. Software engineering practices**\n",
        "Python has mature tooling for testing (`pytest`), packaging (`pip`/`poetry`), version control workflows, and containerisation (`Docker`) — essential when regression code moves into production.\n",
        "\n",
        "**6. Quarto and notebook support**\n",
        "Python integrates seamlessly with Quarto, Jupyter, and VS Code, enabling reproducible, publication-quality documents (like this one).\n",
        "\n",
        "## Disadvantages of Python (Compared to R)\n",
        "\n",
        "**1. Statistical output is less rich out of the box**\n",
        "R's `lm()` and related functions were purpose-built by statisticians. `summary(lm(...))` in R prints p-values, significance stars, and diagnostic cues with a single call. `statsmodels` matches most of this, but the ecosystem for niche statistical methods (mixed models, survival analysis, Bayesian hierarchical models) is generally more mature in R.\n",
        "\n",
        "**2. Formula syntax is a secondary concern**\n",
        "R's formula interface (`y ~ x1 + x2`) is native to the language. In Python, `statsmodels` adds it as a convenience layer (`smf.ols(\"y ~ x1 + x2\")`), but base Python has no concept of formulas — this can feel bolted-on for statisticians.\n",
        "\n",
        "**3. Tidyverse-style data wrangling**\n",
        "R's `tidyverse` (`dplyr`, `tidyr`, `ggplot2`) provides an exceptionally coherent and readable grammar for data manipulation and visualisation. `pandas` and `seaborn` cover similar ground but with less syntactic consistency.\n",
        "\n",
        "**4. Academic statistics community defaults to R**\n",
        "Most econometrics, biostatistics, and social science textbooks and journals use R. Replicating published analyses often requires translating R code, which adds friction.\n",
        "\n",
        "**5. Verbose setup for simple tasks**\n",
        "Running a quick regression in R takes three lines. In Python, you typically import five libraries and manage more boilerplate before reaching the model.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Quick Comparison Table\n",
        "\n",
        "| Criterion | Python (`statsmodels`) | R (`lm`) |\n",
        "|-----------|----------------------|----------|\n",
        "| Formula interface | ✅ Via `smf` | ✅ Native |\n",
        "| Summary output | ✅ Detailed | ✅ Detailed + stars |\n",
        "| ML integration | ✅ Excellent (`sklearn`) | 🔶 Good (`caret`, `tidymodels`) |\n",
        "| Visualisation | ✅ `matplotlib` / `seaborn` | ✅ `ggplot2` (often preferred) |\n",
        "| Niche stat methods | 🔶 Growing | ✅ Very mature |\n",
        "| Production deployment | ✅ Excellent | 🔶 Possible but less common |\n",
        "| Learning curve (stats focus) | 🔶 Moderate | ✅ Lower for statisticians |\n",
        "| Ecosystem breadth | ✅ Very broad | 🔶 Primarily stats/data |\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-tip}\n",
        "## When to Use Which\n",
        "Choose **Python** when your work sits within a broader data engineering or ML pipeline, your team is mixed (engineers + analysts), or you need to deploy models as services.\n",
        "Choose **R** when your work is primarily statistical inference, your audience is academic, or you heavily rely on specialised statistical packages.\n",
        "Many practitioners use both — Python for pipelines and deployment, R for exploratory analysis and publication figures.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
